\section{Introduction}

% \textbf{General Issue }

Variations and trends in the climate of Earth can be studied by observations of the climate, by climate simulations, or by a merging of the two such that the model-simulated variables are constrained by observed information. 
This latter approach is generally known as data assimilation.
Though data assimilation originated in the context of numerical weather forecasting, is now frequently applied to climate simulations, and in fact is now accessible non-experts via out-of-the-box assimilation toos tools such as the Data Assimilation Research Testbed \citep[DART]{andersonetal2009} or the Parallel Data Assimilation Framework \citep[PDAF]{Nerger2013}.

%\textbf{Scientific context and state of the art}

It is not immediately clear, however, what observations should be used to constrain a given simulation.
A relatively new source of information about the Earth system exists in the form of space geodesy, i.e. the measurement of the figure, position, and geoid of the Earth from satellites, very long baseline interferometry, and satellite and lunar laser ranging.  
Here we explore the potential for a certain kind of geodetic monitoring data, namely the so-called Earth Rotation Parameters, or ERPs, for data assimilation.

The ERPs represent global measures of the Earth's angular momentum, and therefore the exchange of angular momentum between the solid Earth and its fluid shell. On timescales shorter than a few years, these angular momentum exchanges are dominated by the atmosphere and ocean. 
Consequently, ERP measurements reflect a variety of atmospheric phenomena.
For example, \citet{Neef2014} showed that sudden stratospheric warmings are typically preceded by a circa 60 milli-arcsecond wobble in the polar orientation, 3-4 weeks before the warming onset.
It is therefore desirable to use such observations to improve the prediction and modeling of events like stratospheric warmings, e.g. by assimilating these observations into prediction models.

%% uncomment if we do end up showing something about gpsro
%GPS-RO measurements have been shown to add a high amount of information to numerical weather forecasts (Bonavita, 2013), due to their low systematic errors and high vertical resolution. It was shown by (Wang et al., 2013) that GPS-RO data give an unprecedented look into the vertical structure of the atmosphere because of their high vertical resolution, in this case showing a warming trend in the tropopause inversion layer that would not have been observed otherwise.

%\textbf{Specific problem / question}


While the prospect of assimilating non-gridpoint observations like ERPs is an exciting possibility, these observations represent integrals of the model state and their assimilation with standard algorithms is therefore not straightforward.
\cite{Saynisch2011,Saynisch2010,Saynisch2012} assimilated ERPs into ocean model simulations, and showed that large adjustments in the model's mass distribution and currents are are necessary in order to acheive a fit to observed ERPs.
However, those studies did not show how much of this change was due to the addition of the integral observations, nor whether or not the ERP observations actually added information to gridpoint observations that were also assimilated.
% GPS-RO measurements, on the other hand, appear to be an ideal observation type to constrain short climate simulations, but it is still unclear how well these observations may constrain an atmospheric model for the purpose of climate studies.

It is usually difficult to judge whether the assimilation of a given set of observations has actually succeeded in bringing the estimated state closer to the truth. 
\textcolor{blue}{It is not sufficient to evaluate the fit between the model and the observations, since the assimilation algorithm is designed to fit the observations. In so-called Observing System Simulation Experiments (OSSEs) a model is used to simulate a "true" state, from which observations are generated and assimilated back into either the same or another model. OSSEs make it possible to evaluate an observation configuration and/or an assimilation technique because the true state is known, and can be directly compared to the analysis model state. In experiments with real observations, it is necessary to compare the assimilated state with independent observations. However, these are often difficult to obtain because different observing systems often don't overlap sufficiently in time and space.}

%
% \textbf{Solution}
In this study we demonstrate the limitations of  using Earth rotation data as a model constraint.
We also demonstrate how the modeled excitation of Earh rotation variations by the angular momentum of the atmosphere can be used as a measure of the assimilation quality, by implementing ERPs as an observation type in the  community data assimilation facility DART.
\textcolor{blue}{We then use the ERPs in idealized experiments to evaluate the potential of GPS-RO observations as a data constraint, and to estimate how much information such observations offer.}

This study is concerned mainly with data assimilation for climate studies, as opposed to data assimilation for numerical weather prediction (NWP). In NWP, observing systems are generally evaluated in terms of forecast skill, i.e. some measure of how the forecast, fol lowing the assimilation, deviates from the true state. Here, we instead focus on assimilation efficacy and fidelity. Efficacy refers to the ability of an assimilation system to effect a positive improvement in a modeled state. Fidelity refers to the ability of the system to return error statistics that are as close as possible to the true error statistics.

%
% \textbf{Costs / benefits}: 
% FILL IN some costs and benefits
