%-------------------------------------METHODS-----------------------------------------------------------------

\section{Data Assimilation System}
Assimilation experiments are performed using the Ensemble Adjustment Kalman Filter \citep[EAKF]{anderson2001} and the Community Atmosphere Model 5 \citep[CAM5]{nealeetal2011}, using the Data Assimilation Research Testbed \citep[DART]{andersonetal2009, raederetal2012}.


\subsection{Atmospheric Model}
CAM5 is run with the finite-volume dynamical core with a $1.9x2.5$ degree lat/lon horizontal resolution, and  30 hybrid-coordinate vertical levels, with a top near 3 hPa.
\textcolor{red}{How is CAM damped at the top?}
CAM5 forms the atmospheric component of the Community Earth System Model (CESM).

\subsection{Data Assimilation}
DART is an open-source, community facility that makes ensemble data assimilation available for any model, using any observations.
It is available online at \url{www.image.ucar.edu/DAReS/DART}.

The EAKF algorithm sequentially updates an ensemble of model simulations based on a spread of the ensemble about its mean, and the distance between the observed value and the observation that would be predicted by that ensemble member.
Here "model state" refers to the full fields of whatever model variables are chosen to be updated; in the case of our experiments, the model state is given by the meridional and zonal winds, the surface pressure, the temperature, and the relative humidity.
The entire state has a dimension of $n = **$ values.

The update is made by estimating the \textit{background} error  covariance matrix for the model state at each observation time, which is simply a function of the spread of the ensemble about its mean.
\begin{eqnarray}
{\bf P}^{\text{b}} = 
\left<
\left(	{\bf x}^{\text{b}}_i - \left<{\bf x}^{\text{b}}\right> \right)
\left(	{\bf x}^{\text{b}}_i - \left<{\bf x}^{\text{b}}\right> \right)^{\text{T}}
\right> 
,
\end{eqnarray}
where the brackets $\left< \cdot \right>$ represent the ensemble average.

When an observation is made, the so-called \textit{analysis} error covariance matrix, ${\bf P}^{\text{a}}$, is reduced proportional to the uncertainty of the observations:
\begin{eqnarray}
 {\bf P}^{\text{a}} =
  %\left[
  %{\bf P^{\text{b}}} + 
  %{\bf H}^{\text{T}}{\bf R}^{-1}{\bf H}
  %\right]^{-1},
  {\bf P}^{\text{b}}
  \left[
  {\bf I} - {\bf K}{\bf H}
  \right],
\label{eq:Pa}
\end{eqnarray}
where \textbf{R} represents the $m \times m$ error covariance matrix of the observations,  ${\bf H}$ represents the operation mapping the state to the observations, and ${\bf I}$ is the $n \times n$ identity matrix.
The so-called gain matrix \textbf{K} is a function of the relative magnitudes of the background and observation errors at each point in the observation space:
\begin{eqnarray}
 {\bf K} = {\bf P}^{\text{f}}{\bf H}\left[	{\bf H}{\bf P}^{\text{f}}{\bf H}^{\text{T}} +{\bf R}	\right]^{-1},
\end{eqnarray}
where ${\bf R}$ represents the error covariance matrix of the observations.
Note that $ {\bf K}$ includes the mapping from state-space to observation-space.  
The individual entries of the gain matrix are close to 1 for small observation errors (in this case the observations are given maximal weight), and close to zero for large observation errors (in which case the observations are given very little weight).  

Having computed (\ref{eq:Pa}), 
The updated ensemble mean of a Gaussian distribution with covariance given by (\ref{eq:Pa}) is
\begin{eqnarray}
  \left< {\bf x}^{\text{a}} \right> = 
  {\bf P}^{\text{a}}
  \left[
  \left({\bf P}^{\text{b}}\right)^{-1} \left< {\bf x}^{\text{b}} \right> + {\bf H}^{\text{T}}{\bf R}^{-1}{\bf y}^{\text{obs}}
  \right].
\label{eq:xa}
\end{eqnarray}
 
In practice we don't actually compute (\ref{eq:Pa}) or (\ref{eq:xa}), but rather the analysis ensemble that represents the analysis error covariance.  
To find the ensemble perturbations that correspond to the posterior error covariance ${\bf P}^{\text{a}}$ (\ref{eq:Pa}), we make use of the fact that the covariance matrix can be written as  ${\bf P}^{\text{a}} = {\bf A}{\bf P}^{\text{b}}{\bf A}^{\text{T}}$,
where the matrix ${\bf A}$ includes a singular-value decomposition of ${\bf P}^{\text{b}}$, which rotates it into a reference frame where it is diagonal, a normalization step, and the analysis update step (\ref{eq:Pa}).
It can then be shown that the ensemble perturbations corresponding to the updated error covariance matrix are given by
\begin{eqnarray}
 {\bf x}_i^{\text{a}} - \left< {\bf x} \right>^{\text{a}} = 
  {\bf A}^{\text{T}}
  \left(
{\bf x}_i^{\text{b}} - \left< {\bf x} \right>^{\text{b}}
  \right).
\end{eqnarray}

\textcolor{red}{Add a statement of how we do the SVD in practice -- how we make all this computationally feasible.}


The main advantage of using ensemble filter assimilation algorithms such as the EAKF is that covariances between components of the model state and the observations are estimated using an ensemble, which itself is updated with the observed information at each analysis time.
This allows us to avoid making a prior estimate of covariances, which can lead to spurious analysis increments, especially at higher levels \citep{Polavarapu2005}.

\subsection{Perfect-model experiments}
\label{sec:experiments}
% perfect model experiments
In this study we  perform so-called perfect-model experiments, wherein the ``truth'' is actually a model simulations, and observations are generated from this simulation with known error statistics, then assimilated back into the model.
Perfect model experiments are designed to show how much information can truly be recovered by assimilation; this is impossible to do with the assimilation of real observations, where the true state is not known.

Experiments are performed with an 80-member ensemble, which  is generated from one full year of assimilation of the uniform grid of radiosonde observations described in Section \ref{sec:radiosondes}.

% observation generation
Two types of observations are generated from the simulated true state: (a) the ERPs, described in Section \ref{sec:AAM}, and (b) an idealized grid of radiosonde observations, described in Section \ref{sec:radiosondes}, as a simple representation of the current grid of conventional observations.

% output diagnostics
Our main evaluation diagnostic is root mean square error (RMSE) between the simulated true state and the ensemble mean.
To evaluate how much information is actually gained from assimilation in each case, the RMSE for each case will be shown relative to a case where the 80-member initial ensemble is evolved forward in time without assimilation, hereafter known as the``No-DA'' run.


\subsection{Atmospheric Angular Momentum Observations}
\label{sec:AAM}
We generate synthetic observations of ERPs by computing the atmospheric angular momentum (AAM) of the model state at each observation time.
The AAM is computed using the following non-dimensional equations derived by \citet{barnesetal1983}:
\begin{eqnarray}
{\bf \chi}_{1}(t) &=& \frac{1.608}{\Omega \left( C-A' \right)}
  \left[ 0.684 \Omega \Delta {\bf I}_{13}(t) + \Delta h_1(t)  \right] \label{eq:X1} \\
{\bf \chi}_{2}(t) &=& \frac{1.608}{\Omega \left( C-A' \right)}
  \left[ 0.684 \Omega \Delta {\bf I}_{23}(t) + \Delta h_2(t)  \right] \label{eq:X2}\\
{\bf \chi}_{3}(t) &=& \frac{0.997}{\Omega C_m}
  \left[ 0.750 \Omega \Delta {\bf I}_{33}(t) + \Delta h_{3}(t) \label{eq:X3} \right].
\end{eqnarray}
Here the ${\bf I}_{ij}$ terms represent components of the atmospheric inertia tensor:
\begin{eqnarray}
  I_{13} &=& -\int R^2 \cos \phi \sin \phi \cos \lambda dM 
  \label{eq:I1}\\
  I_{23} &=& -\int R^2 \cos \phi \sin \phi \sin \lambda dM 
  \label{eq:I2}\\
  I_{33} &=&  \int R^2 \cos^2 \phi dM ,
  \label{eq:I3}
\end{eqnarray}
and the $h_i$ terms he relative angular momentum (due to winds) in each direction:
\begin{eqnarray}
  h_{1}  &=& -\int R \left[u \sin \phi \cos \lambda - v \sin \lambda \right] dM 
    \label{eq:h1}\\
  h_{2}  &=& -\int R \left[u \sin \phi \sin \lambda + v \cos \lambda \right] dM 
    \label{eq:h2}\\
  h_{3}  &=&  \int R u \cos \phi dM.
    \label{eq:h3}
\end{eqnarray}
%
$R = 6371.0$ km is the radius of the Earth, $\Omega = 7.292115\times 10^{-5} \text{rad}/\text{s}$ the average rotation rate, and $g = 9.81 \text{m}/\text{s}^2$ is the acceleration due to gravity.
 $C = 8.0365 \times 10^{37} \text{kg} \text{m}^2$ and $A = 8.0101 \times 10^{37} \text{kg} \text{m}^2$ are the  axial and next-largest principal moments of inertia of the solid Earth, and $C_m = 7.1236 \times 10^{37} \text{kg} \text{m}^2$ is the principal inertia tensor component of the Earth's mantle \citep{gross2009}.

In reality, of course, we don't measure the atmospheric angular momentum but rather the variations in the ERPs that are excited by the above angular momentum functions.
The non-dimensional representation of AAM in (\ref{eq:X1})-(\ref{eq:X3}) makes it easy to map angular momentum changes to equivalent changes in the polar orientation (or polar motion) and the rate of Earth's rotation. 
Polar motion is defined by two angular anomalies in the orientation of the rotational pole, $p_1$, defined along the Greenwich meridian, and $p_2$,  defined along 90$\degree$E.  
Their variation is related to variations in the equatorial AAM functions (\ref{eq:X1})-(\ref{eq:X2})  by a rotation of the reference frame:
\begin{eqnarray}
  p_1 + \frac{\dot{p_2}}{\sigma_0} &=& \chi_1 \\
  -p_2 + \frac{\dot{p_1}}{\sigma_0} &=& \chi_2,
\label{eq:X12_to_PM}
\end{eqnarray}
where $\sigma_0 = 433$d represents the Chandler frequency, a free nutation of the solid Earth that is due the fact that the Earth is not a perfect sphere, which causes a difference between the Earth's polar axis and its figure axis \citep{Gross2000}.

The axial AAM function $\chi_3$ corresponds to unit changes in the rate of rotation of the Earth, and therefore also unit anomalies in the length of a day ($\Delta$LOD):
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\Delta \text{LOD}}{ \text{LOD}_0 } &=& \Delta \chi_3,
\label{eq:X3_to_LOD}
\end{eqnarray}
where $\text{LOD}_0$ denotes the sidereal length-of-day (86164s).  The length-of-day anomalies are observed as $\Delta \text{LOD}  \equiv \text{UT1} - \text{IAT}$ where UT1 denotes the universal time measured by geodetic techniques and IAT is a reference time based on atomic clock measurements.

The relations(\ref{eq:X12_to_PM}) and (\ref{eq:X3_to_LOD}) give the equivalent Earth rotation variations due to AAM changes. 
In this study, we will assume for the sake of simplicity that measured ERP variations are completely due to the atmosphere. 
For $\Delta$LOD, this is a valid assumption on the subseasonal timescale.  
For polar motion, the contributions from oceanic angular momentum are of a similar order of magnitude as that of AAM \citep{Neef2012}. 

Note that the zonal integration in the axial AAM terms [(\ref{eq:I3}) and (\ref{eq:h3})] weights all longitudes equally.
In practice, this means that mass anomalies tend to cancel one another out in the zonal integral, with the result that the axial mass excitation (\ref{eq:I3}) is usually several orders of magnitude smaller than the axial wind excitation (\ref{eq:h3}) \citep{barnesetal1983}.

Nearly the opposite is true for the equatorial AAM terms [(\ref{eq:I1})-(\ref{eq:I2}) and (\ref{eq:h1})-(\ref{eq:h2})], where stronger zonal asymmetry in the wind and mass fields leads to a larger global integral.
For these functions, the mass terms [(\ref{eq:I1}) and (\ref{eq:I2})] typically outweigh the wind terms [(\ref{eq:h1}) and (\ref{eq:h2})] by a few factors \citep{barnesetal1983}.


Of the polar motion angles, $p_1$ largely reflects surface pressure variations over the oceans, and $p_2$ over the continents.
Thus $p_2$ has a pronounced annual cycle due to the yearly appearance of the Siberian High \citep{dobslawetal2010}, and tends to show strong negative anomalies in the two months preceding sudden stratospheric warmings \citep[submitted]{neefmatthes2013sub}.
The relative effects of AAM on the two polar motion components on the subseasonal timescale is less clear on the subseasonal timescale, where the effect of surface pressure variations over the ocean tend to be evened out by corresponding displacements of the ocean surface (the so-called ``inverse barometer'' effect), though the extent to which this is really true is unclear \citep{salsteinrosen1989}.

For our experiments, observations of $\chi_1$, $\chi_2$, and $\chi_3$ are generated every 24 hours, reflecting the observation frequency of the real ERP series released by Earth rotation services.  


\subsection{Idealized Conventional Observations}
\label{sec:radiosondes}

In order to evaluate  the assimilation of ERPs, we need to compare it to the assimilation of conventional, spatially-distributed observations such as are normally assimilated in the generation of atmospheric reanalysis \citep{deeetal2005} or weather prediction models (\textcolor{red}{CITE}).
Since compiling all the available observations is a complicated task in itself, we simulate the conventional observation grid using an idealized, global grid of radiosonde-like observations.  

The horizontal grid of the radiosonde observations is shown in Figure **.

\textcolor{red}{What is the horizontal distribution of our radiosonde observations?}

%---first things first: what hole does assimilation fill?  What does a simulation show when we don't assimilate?
\section{Error growth without assimilation}

It is instructive to examine spread of a large ensemble of simulations when no assimilation is performed, because it shows us what can be gained from assimilating in the first place.
Figure \ref{fig:NODA}(a) shows the RMSE (ensemble mean minus true state), as a function of vertical level and time, in the zonal-mean and meridional-mean zonal wind. 
The zonal wind error spreads most rapidly around 300 hPa, i.e. at the altitudes of the extratropical jets.
After about a month, the error also grows strongly at the highest model levels.
  
Comparing the RMSE to the spread in the ensemble over this time [Fig. \ref{fig:NODA}(b)], we see that the ensemble spread is largely commensurate with the growth of error between the ensemble mean and the truth state, which is to be expected since in our experiments the "truth" is a realization of the same model that produced the ensemble.
This is also evident when comparing the globally-average ensemble spread and RMSE  [Fig. \ref{fig:NODA}].

If we now assimilate observations, the state will be adjusted most strongly where the ensemble spread is largest, which in this case is also where the true error is largest.

\textcolor{red}{Also say what it looks like for surface pressure!}



%-------------------------------------RESULTS 1- integral obs suck------------------------------------------------------
\section{Can we constrain the model using global integral observations?}

\subsection{Observation-space Diagnostics}
Figure \ref{fig:fit_to_erps} shows the ensemble estimates of the three ERPs, with and without the assimilation of ERPs. 
The case of no assimilation (Fig. \ref{fig:fit_to_erps}, Column A) starts out with the ensemble clustered closely around each of the true ERPs.
The ensemble spreads noticeably after about a week, and by the end of January, the ensemble mean lacks any of the short-timescale features of the true ERPs.
%\textcolor{red}{Can we say anything to the differences between the three ERPs?}

When ERPs are assimilated (Fig. \ref{fig:fit_to_erps}, Column B), the ensemble members naturally agree much more in their predicted ERPs.  
Thus the assimilation of ERPs is ``successful'' in the sense that the wind and surface pressure fields in each ensemble member are nudged enough to give each ensemble member an AAM vector that is close to what is observed.
However, success in fitting the assimilated variables does not automatically imply that the state variables themselves are closer to the true state.  
This will be investigated in the following section.

\subsection{Error reduction in Wind and Pressure Fields}

Figure \ref{fig:ERPDA} shows the RMSE of (a) the surface pressure and (b) the 300hPa zonal-mean zonal wind, and (c) the meridional-mean zonal-mean zonal wind, relative to their respective errors in the NODA experiment.
Negative values indicate a reduction in error relative to no assimilation.  

In all fields shown, error is reduced in most regions during the first month of assimilation.
In general, the most error reduction happens in the regions where the ensemble spread is the greatest: at high latitudes for surface pressure,  in the extratropical jet regions for zonal wind, and near the model top.
Thus the fitting of the state to the observed ERPs [Fig. \ref{fig:fit_to_erps}] also results in an overall correction to the model state for the first month or so.

Figure \ref{fig:global} shows the globally-averaged RMSE in surface pressure, the 10hPa zonal wind, and the 300hPa zonal wind as a function of time, comparing the ERPALL and NODA experiments.
\textcolor{red}{Do we see an overall improvement for the first month, at least in U300?}
\textcolor{red}{What can we say about the large increments at the highest levels?}

However, regions where error is increased relative to no assimilation (yellow in Fig. \ref{fig:ERPDA}) appear more and more in the second month of assimilation, which means that fitting the model to the observed ERPs makes the ensemble state estimate worse.  




\subsection{Evolution of the Ensemble-Estimated Covariance Field}

The degree to which each variable field is changed as the assimilation progresses depends on the covariances between local wind or surface pressure, and the global AAM functions.
The evolution of these covariances in time is estimated by the ensemble. 
It is easiest to examine the ensemble covariances by looking at the analysis increment, i.e. EQUATION, where DEFINITIONS.
The difference between the observed and predicted ERPs (FILL IN) is mapped to the state by the gain matrix \textbf{K}, which is given by EQUATION.

In the case of ERP assimilation, \textbf{K} has three rows (one for each ERP), and as many columns as there are state variables.
\textcolor{red}{How many state variables do we have?}
Each term has the following structure: \textcolor{red}{EQUATION}, i.e. each term is proportional to the covariance between that particular state variable and the global AAM exictation function, normalized by the total prior variance of the global AAM and its corresponding ERP observation.  
Note that the inverse part of (**) is simply a $3 \times 3$ matrix, and that 
the same normalization is applied to the gain that is applied to every state vector element.
Thus the innovation are a sort of proxy for the local-to-global covariances.

Figure  \ref{fig:innovations} shows the innovation (Prior-Posterior) in the same fields shown in Fig. \ref{fig:ERPDA}.


\subsection{Can Earth rotation observations add value?}

Though it was seen in Section ** that the assimilation of ERP observations can reduce error in the modeled wind and pressure fields, it is not yet clear whether or not this error reduction complements the information given by more conventional observations, such as radiosonde winds and temperatures, and GPS-RO refractivities.  

Figure \ref{fig:global} shows the global RMSE in the four experiments introduced in Section **.  

