%------------------------------------summary and conclusions-------------------------
\section{Summary}  

\begin{itemize}
 \item The assimilation of Earth Rotation Parameters is able to constrain an ensemble simulation of the atmosphere, but the error reduction that these observations bring does not last beyond the first few days of assimilation.  The reason for this is that the constraint offered by these observations, which represent integrals of the wind and mass fields, is too weak.
%
 \item There exists a potential way to assimilate integral observations, based on the study of \citet{Dirren2005}, but applying this method is doubtful to offer improvements upon the assimilation of other available observations, such as GPS-RO measurements.  
%
 \item The real usefulness of Earth rotation observations is that they can measure the efficacy and fidelity of a data assimilation system, allowing us to evauluate a wide range of global-scale phenomena, including the MJO, ENSO, and the precursors to SSWs, within three independently-observed numbers.
%
 \item In particular \textcolor{red}{fill in the individual results for the three excitation functions.}
\end{itemize}



